Comparing two folders directly within Neovim isn't a native feature like comparing two files, but because Neovim is highly extensible, you have three solid ways to do it depending on how much "extra" stuff you want to install.

1. The Built-in Way (Using vimdiff)
While Neovim doesn't have a "directory diff" mode out of the box, you can leverage the underlying shell. If you are on a Unix-like system (Linux/macOS), you can run this from your terminal:

Bash
nvim -d <(ls folder1) <(ls folder2)
How it works: This passes the file lists of both folders into Neovim's diff mode.

Pro: No plugins required.

Con: You can only see which filenames differ; you can't "dive into" the files to see content differences from here.

2. The Plugin Way (Recommended)
If you want a visual, side-by-side directory tree where you can expand folders and see exactly what’s different, you need a plugin.

DirDiff.vim
This is the classic choice for this specific task.

Command: :DirDiff folder1 folder2

Features: It opens two windows side-by-side. If you press Enter on a file, it opens a diff of those two specific files.

Diffview.nvim
If you are using Git, Diffview.nvim is the gold standard. It provides a dedicated tab for cycling through changed files.

Command: :DiffviewOpen (to compare branches/commits) or :DiffviewOpen -- folder1 folder2.

3. The "Quick & Dirty" Terminal Toggle
If you just want to see the differences without fancy buffers, you can call the standard system diff from inside Neovim:

Vim Script
:!diff -qr folder1 folder2
-q: Brief (tells you if files differ without showing code).

-r: Recursive (looks inside subfolders).

Comparison Table
Method	Best For	Ease of Use
Terminal nvim -d	Quick filename checks	Medium
DirDiff Plugin	Deep folder synchronization	Easy
Diffview Plugin	Git-heavy workflows	Advanced
Shell :!diff	Fast "yes/no" comparison	Instant
